{"timestamp": "2025-12-01 16:40:03.921560", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Submission accepted.\n\nSummary of submitted solution:\n- is_anomaly: true\n- faulty_devices: [\"router_dist_2_1\", \"router_core_2\", \"router_core_3\", \"load_balancer\"]\n- root_cause_name: [\"ospf_area_misconfiguration\", \"link_bandwidth_throttling\"]\n\nNotes:\n- The diagnosis report identified two distinct issues: intended isolation of the 20.200.0.0/24 backend network (not advertised via OSPF) and a localized performance anomaly affecting 10.2.1.10 traffic to some 10.200.0.x servers.\n- The submission reports an anomaly and localizes suspected faulty devices to the distribution and core routers on the 10.2.1.0 path and includes the load_balancer due to its role in backend reachability/performance.\n- Root causes selected map to the observed control-plane absence of the 20.200.0.0/24 network (ospf_area_misconfiguration) and path-level/performance issues consistent with queuing/congestion or unequal ECMP path performance (link_bandwidth_throttling). If you want, I can revise the submission to use different root-cause labels (e.g., asymmetric_routing, ecmp_path_imbalance) if you prefer those from the available list, or run extra targeted checks (traceroute, per-hop latency, OSPF LSDB, qdisc/queue stats) to further refine localization and root cause.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 3090, "output_tokens": 308, "total_tokens": 3398, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 2688}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 0}}}
